Introduction

This case study is for the Google & Coursera Data Analytics Certificate. Bellabeat is a high-tech manufacture of fitness devices for women. The primary focus of these devices are to track and give analysis on sleep, fitness, and other health related patterns.

Some of these primary products include:

  • Bellabeat App - Connects to other Bellabeat devices to provide users information on their health, sleep cycles, fitness, mindfulness habits, and more.

  • Leaf - This is a wellness tracker that can be worn as a bracelet, necklace, or clip. This is the classic fitness device in the Bellabeat line.

  • Time - This wellness watch combines the aesthetic as a natural timepiece while having the smart technology capabilities to track users sleep patterns, steps, and stress. Connects to the Bellabeat App to give insights to your wellness.

  • Spring - This is a water bottle that tracks your daily water intake using smart technology to ensure you are appropriately hydrated throughout the day. The bottle also connects to the Bellabeat App.

  • Bellabeat membership: Bellabeat also offers a subscription-based membership program for users. Membership gives users 24/7 access to fully personalized guidance on nutrition, activity, sleep, health and beauty, and mindfulness based on their lifestyle and goals.

1. ASK

Stakeholders

  • Urška Sršen: Bellabeat’s cofounder and Chief Creative Officer

  • Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeat’s cofounder; key member of the Bellabeat executive team

  • Bellabeat marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Bellabeat’s marketing strategy.

More About the Company

Urška Sršen and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat, a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products. Sršen used her background as an artist to develop beautifully designed technology that informs and inspires women around the world. Collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has allowed Bellabeat to empower women with knowledge about their own health and habits. Since it was founded in 2013, Bellabeat has grown rapidly and quickly positioned itself as a tech-driven wellness company for women.

Business Task

I was given data from FitBit Fitness Trackers made available through Kaggle. I was tasked with cleaning and analyzing this data to help the marketing team on Bellabeat make decisions moving forward. This data set was created between 03/12/2016-05/12/2016 and contains personal fitness tracker from thirty fitbit users.

Questions to Consider during the analysis

  1. What are some trends in smart device usage?

  2. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?

  3. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Daily_Activity <- dailyActivity_merged %>% rename (Date = ActivityDate)

3. ANALYZE & SHARE

Now that I have cleaned each data frame properly, I will merge data frames that I want to analyze further by ID & Date. Since elements of the Daily_Intensities dataframe are already in the Daily_Activities data frame, I will focus on merging the Daily_Activities and Sleep_Day_Clean dataframes to further analyze patterns of fitness intensities, calorie burning, and sleep patterns. After merging, I will preview the data to ensure it merged properly.

Daily_Activity_Sleep <- merge(Daily_Activity,Sleep_Day_Clean, by =c("Id","Date"))

With my process of this analysis, I want to find out the total averages for the data given to us by each user ID. I then create a new dataset taking the individual records from each user in Daily_Activity_Sleep and create a new dataframe that has the average of each data point collected from each user.

Activity_Sleep_Avg <- Daily_Activity_Sleep %>% group_by(Id)%>% summarize(avg_TotalSteps=mean(TotalSteps),avg_TotalDistance=mean(TotalDistance),avg_Calories=mean(Calories),avg_TotalMinutesInBed=mean(TotalTimeInBed),avg_TotalMinutesAsleep=mean(TotalMinutesAsleep),avg_SedentaryTime=mean(SedentaryMinutes))

Now I want to visualize certain elements of this data so we can see any trends.

ggplot(data=Activity_Sleep_Avg)+ geom_point(mapping=aes(x=avg_TotalSteps,y=avg_Calories))+labs(title="Average Total Steps vs Average Calories Burned")

Lets break the visualization down further than averages. The data broken down will be a bit scrambled, so I want to use a trend line in an attempt to see if there is correlation between steps and calories per user on days where intensity might have varied.

ggplot(data = Daily_Activity_Sleep,mapping = aes(x=TotalSteps, y=Calories)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Correlation Between Steps and Calories")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

I decided to visualize the data of comparing users very active distance to calories burned. However, with some users not recording any very active distance, I will create a new data frame that omits users with 0 very active distance recorded.

VeryAcitve_data <- subset(Daily_Activity_Sleep, VeryActiveDistance != 0)
ggplot(data = VeryAcitve_data,mapping = aes (x=VeryActiveDistance, y=Calories)) + labs(title = "Very Active Distance vs Calories Burned") + geom_point() + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

I want to start by looking at the average of users total time in bed spent, versus their total time asleep.

ggplot(data = Activity_Sleep_Avg, mapping = aes(x = avg_TotalMinutesInBed, y = avg_TotalMinutesAsleep)) + labs(title = "Average Total Time In Bed vs Asleep") + geom_point() + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Next, I want to compare sleep trends to calories and steps to look for any correlation

ggplot(data = Daily_Activity_Sleep, mapping = aes (x = TotalMinutesAsleep, y = TotalSteps)) + labs(title = "Total Minutes Asleep vs Total Steps") + geom_point() + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

This data was good to visualize, because it shows that users who get an average of 360 - 480 minutes of sleep do record the most amount of steps taken. Next I want to take it a step further by comparing total sleep and calories burned.

ggplot(data = Daily_Activity_Sleep, mapping = aes(x = TotalMinutesAsleep, y = Calories)) + labs(title = "Total Minutes Asleep vs Calories Burned") + geom_point() + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

This visualization confirms my same process from total time asleep v. steps taken. The users who record sleep from 360 - 480 minutes, or 6-8 hours of sleep, burn the most amount of calories.

Conclusion

Analyzing this data had its limitations, however gives the Bellabeat team a good idea in what to focus on with its users moving forward. The limitations of the dataset focuses around the fact that, the sample size in this dataset is relatively small, being only 30 users. However, with these 30 users, it gave me a versatile amount of data to work with; being users who range from not active, to very active, and users who get a low amount of sleep to those who get an overabundance.

Recommendations

In reference to my report to the Bellabeat marketing team and its stakeholders, these would be my key focal points:

When researching sleep recommendations, the National Library of Medicine has an article posted around the recommended amount of sleep in adults. They recommend around 7 hours, with less than 7 hours attributing to adverse health outcomes, and over 9 hours promoting health risks as well. The Bellabeat marketing team can use this information to distribute recommendations to its users, who have particular fitness goals, that could be potentially recording not enough sleep, to the users who are getting too much sleep.

Thank you.
